es in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Reynold  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Reynold","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Anglo-Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Reinald</i>, <i>Reynaud</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Raginald</i>, from <i>ragin</i> ‘counsel, decision’ + <i>wald</i> ‘rule, ruler’), first introduced to England by Scandinavian settlers in the Old Norse form <i>Rögnvaldr</i> (see   Ronald  ) and greatly reinforced after the Conquest by the Norman forms <i>Reinald</i> and <i>Reynaud</i>, which often appear Latinized as <i>Reginaldus</i>. The surname was later much confused with   Raynor   and   Renard  . The surname is occasionally also borne by Jews, in which case it presumably represents an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":6,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":26,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":36,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter de Reynell I was born in 1060, in Pitney, Somerset, England, his father, Arnoul de Reynel, was 16 and his mother, Blanche of Somerset, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth de Joseph. He died in 1152, in Pitney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 92, and was buried in Pitney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1060–1152":"1060–1152","1064–Female":"1064–Surnud","1080–1104":"1080–1104","1045–1062":"1045–1062","1035–1060":"1035–1060","1080":"1080","Aft 1104":"pärast 1104","after 1060":"pärast 1060","1066":"1066","1152":"1152","1086":"1086","1064":"1064","1096":"1096","1062":"1062","1060":"1060","1104":"1104","1035":"1035","1045":"1045","Abt 1080":"umbes 1080","France":"Prantsusmaa","Pitney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Pitney, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pitney, Somerset, England":"Pitney, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"1060–1152":"1060–1152","1064–Female":"1064–Kuollut","1080–1104":"1080–1104","1045–1062":"1045–1062","1035–1060":"1035–1060","1